replies.bodyText:
Hi @jomarko both scenarios are the same, so I'll only try to explain once here.
There is the outer wrapper around the inner core editor.
Both the outer wrapper and inner core implement DiagramEditorCore. The wrapper is the "public" class that integrates with Business Central or kogito (depending on it's implementation) and the inner core is the editor itself. The inner core editor should delegate all operations to the outer wrapper - as it is the outer wrapper that can have methods overridden in subclasses (as was indeed the issue here.. the inner core was calling a method on itself rather than delegating to the outer wrapper where @danielzhe overrides a method).
For example:-
class OuterWrapper implements DiagramEditorCore {

  DiagramEditorCore core = new DiagramEditorCore() {

    @Override
    public void anInterfaceMethod() {
      //Delegate to wrapper
      OuterWrapper.this.anInterfaceMethod();
    }
  };

  @Override
  public void anInterfaceMethod() {
    //Do something
  }
}
